{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/0028060530A/1949030201/0741.xml":{"full_text":"Nation's Bank Loans\nShow January Decline\nAfter Rising for Year\nBy Edward C. Stone\nLoans in the nation's 15,000\nbanks declined $220,000,000 during\nJanuary after rising an average of\n$410,000,000 a month for the last\n12 months, the Federal Reserve\nBoard reported today. Total\nloans listed were $48,120,000,000.\nThe weekly report of the Fed\neral Reserve Bank of Richmond,\nout today, showed a slump in de\nmand desposits in Washington\nbanks for the week endig February\n23 of $14,564,000, the total of\n$749,699,000 comparing with $764,\n263.000 in the preceding week.\nTime deposits were up slightly.\nThe report showed a rise of\n$401,000 in commercial loans, also\na small advance in real estate\nloans. Treasury bills dropped\nabout $9,000,000.\nData Sought From Husbands.\nThe Riggs National Bank dis\ntributed in its monthly statements\na unique folder entitled \u201cWhat\nEvery Wife Should Know.\u201d which\ncontains a financial questionnaire\nto be filled out by husbands.\nThe purpose is to have for ready\nreference information as to the\nlocation of wills, life insurance\npolicies, bank accounts, stocks and\nbonds, social security cards and\nnumbers, real estate and personal\nproperty.\nSettlement of estates often has\nbeen greatly hampered by lack of\nvital papers. The folders have\nbeen highly praised by women's\nmagazines.\nPollard Leaves souinern.\nFrank D. Pollard, auditor of dis\nbursements of the Southern Rail\nway System at Washington, re\ntired yesterday after 48 years\u2019\nservice and was succeeded by\nThomas P. Carter, his assistant.\nMr. Pollard was born in Alexan\ndria in 1880 and joined the South\nern as a clerk in 1901. Mr. Carter\nhas been with the road since 1908.\nElection of Thomas B. Thatcher\nas an assistant treasurer of the\nPerpetual Building Association is\nannounced by Edward C. Baltz,\npresident. A native of Brooklyn,\nthe new officer is a graduate of\nTufts College. Medford. Mass., and\nTuiane University. New Orleans.\nThomas H. Wilson has been\nnamed sales manager of the beer j\ndivision of the Paulsam Distrib\nuting Co. He has been here 13'\nyears, much of the time with the:\nHeurich Brewing Co. He belongs\nto the Board of Trade and the\nSales Executives\u2019 Club. Years ago\nhe gained national fame in bas\nket ball.\nVeteran Banker Honored.\nP. Stanley Harrison, president\nof the Hughesville Savings Bank,\nin Maryland, was given a dinner\nlast night in honor of his 40th\nanniversary with the bank and his\n71st birthday.\nM. J. Plodinec is acting con\ntroller of Trans World Airline,\nsucceeding L. R. Gilleran, now\ntreasurer of Encyclopaedia Bri\ntannica.\nShipment of 152 personal air\ncraft by ten companies in January\nis reported by the Washington\noffice of Aircraft Industrie'.\nManager Joseph E. Jones and\nagents of the Mutal Benefit Asso\nciation of Omaha will have a\nluncheon Friday at the ^tatler on j\nthe company's 40th anniversary.\nBusiness Briefs j\nWholesale Food Index, based on\ncost of a pound of each of 31;\nfoods in general use, advanced\nthis week to S5.82 from S5.70 last\nweek, but was 13.1'- below the;\nyear-ago figure of $6.70\u2014Dun\nBradstreet.\nEdison Electric Institute report\ned electric power production for\nweek ended February 26 dropped\nto 5.559.207.000 kilowatt hours\nfrom 5.650.279,000 the previous\nweek. This was 5.9'- above the\n5.251.935.000 of a year ago.\nHoward Hughes announced plans\nto sell his interest in the new\ncompany which will take over the\nRKO theater business under an\nRKO reorganization plan. Mer\nrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner Beane\nand the First Boston Corp. will\nhandle his holdings.\nCentral Railroad Co. of New\nJersey obtained ICC authority to\nmodify outstanding securities. One\neffect would be to take the rail\nroad out of bankruptcy proceed-1\nings. The plan requires approval\nof 75 of the security holders.\nUnited Fruit Co. earnings for\n1948 were $59,740,231 or $6.81 a\nshare vs. $54,140,794 or $6.17 in\n1947.\nBarnsdall Oil Co. earnings for\n1948 were $13,473,629 or $6.06 a.\nshare vs. $9,119,030 fir $4.10 in\n1947.\nSouthwestern Public Service Co.\nfor year ended January 31 earned\n$3,831,592 or $2.78 a share vs.;\n$3,351,415 or $2.44 in 1947.\nMueller Brass Co. for year\nended November 30 earned $2,\n012,054 or $3.79 a share vs. $2,\n956.338 or $5.56 in 1947.\nMerritt-Chavman Scott Corp.\nin 1948 earned $1,310,838 or $4.17\na share vs. $1,841,907 or $5.94 in\n1947.\nSharon Steel Corp. in 1948\nearned $9,234,983 or $14.96 a\nshare vs. $6,722,019 or $10.89 in\n1947.\nShawinigan Water Tower Co.\nin 1943 earned $4,251,190 or $1.58\na share vs. $3,948,308 or $1.62 in\n1947.\nUnion Asbestos Rubber in\n1948 earned $1,432,924 or $2.89 a\nshare vs. $1,223,418 or $2.47 in\n1947.\nMountain States Tel. Tel. Co.\nin 1948 earned $5,698,911 or $8.30\na share vs. $1,698,451 or $2.95 in\n1947.\nEx-Cell-O Corp. for year ended\nNovember 30 earned $2,498,638 or\n$6.26 a share vs. $2,085,788 or\n$5.23 in 1947.\nHomestake Mining Co. in 1948\nearned $2,445,868 or $1.22 a share\nvs. $2,585,047 or $1.29 in 1947.\nBridgeport Brass Co. in 1948\nearned $1,934,895 or $1.97 a share\nvs $1,213,990 or $1.19 in 1947.\nAtlantic Coast Line Co. in 1948\nearned $1,063,960 or $4.52 a shaie\nvs. $985,133 or $4.19 in 1947.\nGlen Alden Coal Co. in 1948\nearned $6,363,625 or $3.67 a share\nvs. $5,467,865 or $3.15 in 1957.\nR. J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. an\nnounced James A. Gray has been\nnamed chairman of the Board of\nDirectors to succeed S. Clay Wil\nliamse who died recently.\nI N. Y. STOCK EXCHANGE I\n(Furnished by the Associated Pren.) I\nSales\u2014\nStock nd Add i\nDividend Rate. 00. High- Low. 1:15. chge\nABBOT! L! 60a 4 74*4 74*4 74*4+ *4\nA C F-Brlll Mot 1 2*4 2*e 2*4\nAcme Steel 4 1 49 49 49\nAdams Eg 1 10\u00ab 7 17*4 17*4 17*4 14\nAddresscg-M 2a 5 29 29 29 *4\nAdmiral Cp 60a 2 16*4 16*4 JJ\nAir Reduction 1 1 20*4 *0