 Small Turnover\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nNEW YORK, Mar. 2.\u2014The stock\nmarket drifted a little lower today\nafter early indecision.\nSelling pressure was not severe,\nthough, and prices quickly leveled\noff at declines of fractions to a\ni point or so. A substantial num\nber of stocks either held un\nchanged or even moved up a trifle.\nTurnover was slow even in com\nparison with many recently sleepy\nsessions.\nA statement by Secretary of\nthe Treasury Snyder that he does\nnot believe the United States is\nhaving a business decline had lit\ntle. if any, effect on the course of\nstock prices. Optimism on the\npart of Leon Keyserling, vice\nchairman of the President\u2019s Coun\ncil of Economic advisers, was also\nignored for the time being.\nOne unusually large transaction\nwas reported from the floor of the\nexchange. A block of 100,000\nshares of Western Air Lines was\nsold at 5Vi, a decline of V* point.\nThe stock later recovered and\nmoved up a notch or two.\nCentral of New Jersey added\nnearly 2 points on the announce\nment that the Interstate Com\nmerce Commission had approved\nthe road's plan for modification\nof its securities.\nAlso ahead were Goodrich,\nMontgomery Ward, American\nTelephone, Dupont, Santa Fe and\nLoews.\nOn the losing side were United\nStates Steel, Bethlehem, Chrysler,\nUnited States Rubber, Woolworth,\nInternational Harvester, Electric'\nPower Light, American Smelt\ning, American Woolen, Baltimore\nOhio, Chesapeake Ohio,\ni Nickel Plate, Standard Oil New\nI Jersey) and Eastern Air Lines.\n1 Bonds tended lower with stocks.\nUnited States Governments held\nsteady in over-the-counter deal\nings.\nMarket Battle Seen\nBy Ford, Chevrolet\nBy tht Associated Press\nDETROIT, Mar. 2.\u2014General\ni Motors' price cuts suggest a\nkeener Chevrolet-Ford competi\ntive battle may be impending.\nThe Chevrolet price cut was only\n$10 per car, but it brought more\nChevrolet models below the Ford\nprices.\nFord has emphasized it has no\npresent intention of cutting prices.\nBut it plans to increase pro\nduction. A production increase\n\u2014if the market can absorb it\u2014\neasily could lead to a price slash.\nLike Ford. Chevrolet has greatly\nexpanded production facilities.\nAlso it has top priority in the\nGeneral Motors allocation of ma\nterials among its various car\ndivisions.\nSo a battle easily could develop\nthis year between these two major\ncar builders\u2014if labor troubles do\nnot handicap one or the other.\nThe labor troubles, incidentally,\nI need not be in their own plants.\n1 Stoppages in supplier factories\ncan impair production.\nProduce Markets\nBaltimore quotations supplied by the\nUnited States Agriculture Department:\nApples\u2014Firm; offerings light. bush*L\nbaskets and bushel boxe*. U. S Is. 2\u2019/\ninches up \u2018unless otherwise stated), Penn\nsylvania Red Delirious, few. A.00: Golden\nDelicious. 4.00; Ganos. 2*4 inches up.\n2.50; Romes. 3 75-4.00; Virginia Stay\nmans. few, 4 35; boxes wrapped Yorks,\n113s-150s. 4 n\u2018\u00bb.\nPotatoes\u2014Old market dull: 100-pound\nsacks. U S. Is. mostly size A. fern' sales.\nPennsylvania Katahdins. used sacks. 3.50\ntiO: 50-pound sacks, mostly 1.80.\nSweet Potatoes\u2014About steady: bushel\nbasket*. U P. is. Maryland and Virginia\nGoldens. 2.5o-3 00. poorer 2 25: Purrto\nRicans, few. 3 25: white yams. few'. 2.7u.\nSnap Brans Steady.\nSnap beans\u2014Market barely steadv; of\nferings ligh* few sales; Florida, bushel\nhampers. strinRless biack Valentines. 3.n0\n3.5\": few best. 3.75-4.00: poorer. 2.15\n2 \u201c5: others supplies insufficient to ouote.\nLima beans\u2014Market about steady;\nFlorida, bushel hampers. 5 00-5.50\nCabbage\u2014Market slow; weaker hu k:\nFlorida. hush*! baskets, round packed lo\nca\u2019ly. 1.40-1 7 5.\nCarrots\u2014New York. Pennsylvania\nbushel baskets, topped, washed. 75-1.00.\nEggplant\u2014Weaker undertone; few sales:\nFlorida, bushel baskets, medium to large.\n4.00-4.5\": fair Quality. 2.00-2.50.\nEscarole