Mexico\nports. Some grain men thought Govern\nment buying would shift from wheat to\ncorn.\nDealings were not very active and near\nthe end of the first hour wheat was un-;\nchanged to la cent lower, May $2.173a;\ncorn was 3\u00ab to a cent lower. May $1.33, i\nand oats were l\u00ab-l-2 lower. May .67. Soy\nbeans were V2 to 114 cents lower, March\n$2.34*4.\nLittle buying interest was shown in I\nnew-crop wheat deliveries, a weekly report\nof the Weather Bureau confirming trade\nimpressions that the crop was coming\nalong in splendid shape. The new ero\u00bb\nmay create suite a storage and transports*\ntion problem when harvested, grain me*\nsaid.\n\"There were a few complaints of dam*\nage bv ice and heaving during the past\nweek from sections of Kansas. Nebraska\nand Missouri The .Weather Bureau said,\n\"but most -eports indicate that the wheat\ncrop as a wncle is in very good condition.'1\nSome growth has taken place as far North\nas Southern Kansas.\nAnother item which did not create earlT\nbuying enthusiasm was a report by th\u00bb\njoint Senate-House Economic Committee,\nwhich recommended a flexible system or\nfarm price supporters. President Truman\nhas not committed himself on the con\ntroversy between flexible and a straight\n00 per cent of parity support level.\nAnnouncement of APril-June export al*\nlocations was expected by the trade short*\nly, possibly by the end of this week.\nAngola (Portuguese West Africa)\nis fostering a karakul sheep rais\ning industry. _\u2022\nA Stott\nChas.G. g Since 1888\npjlUll s\u00bb a, /\u00bbc.\nSTATIONFRS^\"UFFiCB OUTFITTERS RARER MEKCHAVfl\nequipped office is o\nwell-equipped office\nVisit your nearest Stott\nlocation for\nIS Stationery\nS Furniture\nS Suppliei\nFiling System\nRecord-keepinf\nEquipment\n1310 New York Are. N.W.\n1513 K St. N.W. 822 17th St. N.W.\n8408 Georgia Ave., Silver Spring\nSLigo 7554\nNA. 4181\nSave Now\nfor your\n'vacation\nDon't wait until next summer to save for your\nvacation. NOW is the time t